@node developers "cha_bsr.guide/Developers"

    Files are stored as raw sysex data, but cha_bsr can also
    load files saved from OctaMED's MIDI message editor.
 |  OctaMED support not yet implemented.

    Here is some information on how cha_bsr works internally,
    it is really quite simple, most of the code is very simple
    and just to link the major components together.  Those
    components are the GUI, the internal model, MIDI, and disk
    files.  The GUI acts as a central hub.

    OBJECT bsrtone              -- packs and unpacks sysex data
        #?                          -- read/write variables
        PROC sysexlength()          -- the length of a BSR patch
        PROC issysex(buffer)        -- is buffer a BSR patch?
        PROC fromsysex(buffer)      -- set variables from patch
        PROC tosysex(buffer)        -- fill patch from variables
        -- note: buffer must be length bsrtone.sysexlength() in
           fromsysex() and tosysex()

    OBJECT bsrgui               -- gui structures
        tone                        -- the associated bsrtone
        #?                          -- easygui gadget lists
        PROC fromtone(tone)         -- constructor
        PROC update(source)         -- call after changing
                                       variables, for action
                                       functions and MIDI
        -- note: source can be "GUI" (most gadgets), "GUIC"
           (gadgets with associated MIDI controllers), and others
        -- action functions: most are very simple, the more
           complicated ones are for filter parameters, which
           interact strangely, and parameters associated with
           continuous controllers (envelopes, filter, extra
           controllers); these functions were initially created for
           use as action functions by EasyGUI but it makes sense
           for them to become the central updating mechanism in the
           future

    MODULE cha/mus/midi         -- MIDI interface using CAMD
    MODULE cha/util/string      -- some simple string functions
    MODULE cha/util/memory      -- some simple memory functions
        -- source code to these is released separately, in
           aminet://dev/e/cha_shared.lha (eventually, in the
           meantime email me for them)

    Any questions/suggestions - email me.

@endnode

